140: The crystal classes are a way to categorize the symmetry of crystals based on their symmetry elements and point groups. They are traditionally classified into 32 categories known as the crystal classes, which describe the symmetry operations (such as rotations, reflections, inversions, and mirror planes) that leave the crystal unchanged. These 32 classes are grouped into seven crystal systems: triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, trigonal, hexagonal, and cubic. The crystal classes include specific point groups, and some well-known crystal classes include the cubic class with high symmetry such as m3m (full cubic symmetry), the hexagonal class with sixfold rotational symmetry such as 6/mmm, and the tetragonal class with fourfold symmetry such as 4/mmm. Each crystal class is associated with a particular set of symmetry elements, which determines the physical properties and symmetry-related features of the crystals that belong to each class. Overall, the 32 crystal classes provide a systematic way to describe and categorize the symmetry of all crystalline structures.
